{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488704"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:53:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:53:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"511"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/511"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.59,0.04,0.01,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106170"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/511"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"511"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88642"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"441"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8811"},{"type":"tags","id":"8888"},{"type":"tags","id":"11191"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1874"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45005"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106170","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106170"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic in Alice Springs with a 48-hour history of irritation and discomfort in her right eye. She has noticed redness and watery discharge from the eye. She denies any visual impairment or pain on eye movement. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is diffuse conjunctival injection in the right eye (Image). Corrected visual acuity is 6/6 bilaterally, with a full range of extraocular movements. Pupillary reflexes are intact bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute trachoma","Viral conjunctivitis","Blepharitis","Acute angle closure glaucoma","Episcleritis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E. Most commonly caused by adenovirus, patients typically complain of a red eye with burning, itching, or foreign body sensation. Mildly tender pre-auricular or submandibular lymphadenopathy is often present. The discharge ranges from watery to mucoid. Viral conjunctivitis usually starts in one eye and progresses to involve both eyes after several days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute trachoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a keratoconjunctivitis caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E (serotypes A, B, Ba and C). While prevalent in remote Indigenous communities where hygiene may be poor and overcrowding common, acute trachoma is typically asymptomatic. The characteristic finding of follicles on the subtarsal conjunctiva is not present here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlepharitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with bilateral symptoms including lid erythema, flaking and itching. The nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms and examination findings do not support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E, an ophthalmological emergency, presents with more severe symptoms often accompanied by nausea and vomiting. Visual acuity is typically reduced, and the affected pupil is often mildly dilated with a relative afferent pupillary defect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpiscleritis\u003C/strong\u003E causes more localised and limited injection than conjunctivitis and rarely presents with discharge. Recurrent episodes may be associated with rheumatological conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis and Sj\u00f6gren syndrome, warranting further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most cases of conjunctivitis are viral in origin and present with watery discharge, redness, and mild discomfort.","Viral conjunctivitis typically starts unilaterally and progresses to involve both eyes after several days.","Key differentiating features from other red eye conditions include preserved visual acuity, normal pupillary reflexes, and absence of severe pain."],"references":["Cronau H, Kankanala RR, Mauger T. Diagnosis and management of red eye in primary care. American family physician. 2010 Jan;81(2):137\u201344. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20082509/","Eye emergency manual: an illustrated guide. NSW Agency for Clinical Innovation. Eye Emergency Manual, 3rd Edition. Sydney: ACI; 2023. Available from: https://aci.health.nsw.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0013/155011/ACI-Eye-Emergency-Manual.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88642"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"511"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18587"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18587"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","ur